# Three.js Scene Graph & World Matrix Computation

## Overview
Three.js uses a hierarchical scene graph where each "'`Object3D` has a local
transform (position, rotation, scale) and a derived `matrixWorld` that
accumulates all ancestor transforms.

## Key APIs
- `object.updateMatrixWorld(true)` — recursively computes `matrixWorld` for
  the entire subtree. **Must be called** before reading world-space positions
  in a headless (non-rendering) environment because there is no render loop.
- `object.traverse(callback)` — depth-first walk over all descendants.
- `InstancedMesh` stores per-instance transforms in `instanceMatrix`.
  The OBJExporter does **not** handle InstancedMesh natively — instances must
  be expanded into individual Mesh objects before export.

## InstancedMesh Expansion Pattern
```js
import * as THREE from '"'three';

function expandInstancedMeshes(root) {
  const toRemove = [];
  root.traverse((child) => {
    if (child.isInstancedMesh) {
      const mat = new THREE.Matrix4();
      for (let i = 0; i < child.count; i++) {
        child.getMatrixAt(i, mat);
        const mesh = new THREE.Mesh(child.geometry, child.material);
        mesh.name = "'`${child.name}_inst${i}`;
        mesh.applyMatrix4(mat);
        child.parent.add(mesh);
      }
      toRemove.push(child);
    }
  });
  toRemove.forEach((m) => m.parent.remove(m));
}
```

## Coordinate-Space Rotation (Y-up → Z-up for Blender)
Blender uses Z-up. Three.js uses Y-up. Apply a −90° rotation around X to the
root before export:
```js
root.rotation.x = -Math.PI / 2;
root.updateMatrixWorld(true);
```
